      "final_code": "import sys\nfrom bisect import bisect_left, insort\n\ndef solve():\n    input_data = sys.stdin.buffer.read().split()\n    n = int(input_data[0])\n    a = [int(x) for x in input_data[1:n+1]]\n    \n    # Find longest subsequence with a[i] <= i+1 (1-indexed: a[i-1] <= i)\n    # d[i] = a[i] - i non-increasing, a[i] strictly increasing\n    # Use dp with states\n    \n    # For each element, key = (a[i], d[i]) = (a[i], a[i]-i)\n    # We want strictly increasing a[i] and non-increasing d[i]\n    # d non-increasing means -d non-decreasing\n    \n    # LIS variant: find longest chain where a increases and d decreases (or equal)\n    # Process and use patience sorting on a, tracking d\n    \n    # dp[v] = best (smallest) -d value achievable with subsequence length len ending with a-value = v\n    # Actually standard approach: for each length l, store the minimum possible last -d value\n    # among all subsequences of length l with maximum a value... tricky.\n    \n    # Let's sort by a[i] increasing, break ties by d[i] decreasing (so same a not chosen twice)\n    # Then find LIS on -d (non-decreasing = LIS with equal allowed)\n    \n    candidates = []\n    for i in range(n):\n        val = a[i]\n        pos = i + 1  # 1-indexed\n        if val <= pos:\n            d = val - pos  # d <= 0\n            candidates.append((val, d))\n    \n    # Sort by val increasing, then by d decreasing (to avoid picking two with same val)\n    candidates.sort(key=lambda x: (x[0], -x[1]))\n    \n    # Now find longest non-decreasing subsequence of (-d) values\n    # where val is strictly increasing\n    # Since sorted by val increasing, ties in val: d decreasing means -d increasing\n    # For strictly increasing val, skip ties - but we need to handle carefully\n    # Standard LIS for strictly increasing val: sort by val, for same val take only one\n    # Here same val can't both be in subsequence (need strictly increasing a)\n    # So for same val, we want to pick best d: since d must be non-increasing sequence,\n    # and we pick one per val group, we want the one that extends best.\n    \n    # For non-decreasing -d (i.e., non-increasing d):\n    # patience sort: maintain tails array where tails[i] = smallest -d ending length i+1 subseq\n    \n    tails = []\n    prev_val = -1\n    for val, d in candidates:\n        if val == prev_val:\n            continue  # skip duplicate val (can't use both in strictly increasing subseq)\n        prev_val = val\n        neg_d = -d  # neg_d >= 0, want non-decreasing\n        # find position to insert: longest subseq where last element <= neg_d\n        pos2 = bisect_left(tails, neg_d + 1)  # first index where tails[pos2] > neg_d... \n        # For non-decreasing LIS: bisect_right for strict, bisect_left for non-strict?\n        # We want non-decreasing: can have equal. So find first tail > neg_d\n        from bisect import bisect_right\n        pos2 = bisect_right(tails, neg_d)\n        if pos2 == len(tails):\n            tails.append(neg_d)\n        else:\n            tails[pos2] = neg_d\n    \n    print(len(tails))\n\nsolve()",
